Record.CAVI-Lemma: Fr. of BF/RF cup. Manner of Onesimos (Beazley). Onesimos (Williams). First quarter fifth. Early (Beazley, Williams). *D. Williams, `Onesimos and the Getty Iliuperis,' GVGettyMus 5 (1991) 42 and 44, figs. 3,a-b. *Beazley, JHS 51 (1931) 45/15. ARV(2) 52, 330/1. Cohen, Bilinguals 526/B 133.
Record.CAVI-Subject: Int.: top of a satyr's head, with drinking horn. Ext.: coral red.(1)
Record.CAVI-Inscriptions: Int.: above the satyr's head: [b] καλος[/b], retr.
Record.CAVI-Comments: + Florence fr., which may give the lower half(?) (Beazley). The inscription refers to the satyr, as there is a large vacat fore.
Record.CAVI-Footnotes: (1)Williams says that the coral red suggests that the Ext. may once have been decorated with figures, possibly BF. For the latter, cf. Basel BS 458, CV, Switzerland 6, pl. 3; and Louvre MNB 2042, ABV 400. See also Cohen, Marsyas 15 (1970-71) 9-10. Beazley in ARV(2) says about the Ext.: "A, in bf. on a coral-red ground, (bit of cloak)."

Record.CAVI-Lemma: Fr. of lip or Gordion cup. Unattributed. Sondros, potter. Ca. 550.
Record.CAVI-Subject: A: Handle zone: palmette remains at left. No other decoration preserved.
Record.CAVI-Inscriptions: A: handle zone: Σον[δρος] : με εποιεσε[ν].
Record.CAVI-Comments: The individual letter forms seem very different from those of VG 79,563, more informal and later. But the model seems to have been the same. However, my note also says that Hannestad's rendering is not accurate. The rho nearly a triangle. Four-stroke sigma.
Record.CAVI-Footnotes: {1} One fr. seems to be Beazley, ABV 173/6, although it is not identified by Hannestad, but she seems to have more of the vase than Beazley did, to judge by the second part of the inscription.
